<content>
<para id="fs-id2056356">The previous section described the processes neurons employ to generate and propagate (conduct) an electrical signal down the axon. In this section we will look at how that electrical signal is transmitted to an adjacent neuron or effector cell, and how the effector cell transduces that signal into a response. This happens at the synapse.</para><section id="fs-id2056386">
<title>Synapses</title>
<para id="fs-id1271229">There are two types of connections between electrically active cells, electrical (gap) junctions and chemical synapses. In an <term>electrical junction</term> there is a direct connection between the two cells so that ions can pass directly from one cell to the next. When one cell is depolarized the joined cell also depolarizes as the ions diffuse between the cells. Because the electrical junction is an ion channel, it can transmit signals in both directions and can send both excitatory and inhibitory signals depending on the direction and type of ions flowing through the channels. At a <term>chemical synapse</term>, a signal ligand (called a neurotransmitter) is released from the presynaptic neuron which then binds to and activates a receptor on the postsynaptic cell. The chemically-gated channels at a given synapse on the postsynaptic membrane are all the same type, therefore a chemical synapse is either excitatory or inhibitory, but not both, and the signal is transmitted in one direction, from the presynaptic to the postsynaptic cell. This section will concentrate on the chemical synapse.</para><para id="fs-id1987445">Chemical synapses can occur between a presynaptic and postsynaptic neuron or a neuron and an effector cell (a muscle or gland cell).  When chemical synapses occur between two neurons they are named based on the structures of the neurons that are involved in the synapse.  For example, an <emphasis>axodendritic synapse</emphasis> is a synapse that occurs between the axon of presynaptic neuron and the dendrite of the postsynaptic neuron. An <emphasis>axosomatic synapse</emphasis> occurs between the axon of the presynaptic neuron and the cell body of the postsynaptic neuron. An <emphasis>axoaxonic synapse</emphasis> is where an axon from a modulating neuron synapses with an axon terminal of another neuron, allowing modulation of the effect at that terminal, see <link target-id="fig-Presynaptic_Inhibition" document=""/>. When the synapse occurs between a neuron and an effector it is referred to as a <emphasis>neuroeffector junction</emphasis>. In the case of skeletal muscle the neuroeffector juntion is called a <emphasis effect="italics">neuromuscular junction</emphasis> (NMJ). Neuromuscular junctions will be discussed in more detail when we discuss muscles in <emphasis effect="italics"> Human Physiology Part III: Physical Movement and Defense</emphasis>.</para><para id="eip-331"><figure id="fig-Presynaptic_Inhibition"><media id="mid-Presynaptic_Inhibition" alt="This image shows multiple axon terminals from a single axon. An axon terminal from a different axon makes an axoaxonic connection at one of the axon terminals, releasing an inhibiting neurotransmitter. The two terminals not affected react normally, but the modulated terminal has a reduced response.">
<image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Presynaptic_Inhibition.jpg" width="350"/>
</media>
 
<caption>An axoaxonic synapse allows modulation of the response at a single axon terminal without affecting the other axon terminals originating from that axon.</caption></figure></para><section id="eip-624"><title>Anatomy of a Synapse</title><para id="eip-176">The general anatomy of a synapse can be described by the following features: 
</para><list id="eip-52"><title>Presynaptic Neuron (axon terminal)</title><item><emphasis>Voltage-gated Calcium Channels:</emphasis> are located on the membrane of the presynaptic axon terminal. These channels open when the axon terminal membrane is depolarized by the arrival of an action potential.</item>
<item><emphasis>Calcium:</emphasis> There is a higher concentration of calcium in the ECF than ICF. As calcium ions diffuse through voltage-gated channels into the ICF, they initiate a process that causes fusion of the synaptic vesicles with the terminal membrane and results in exocytosis of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.</item>
<item><emphasis>Synaptic vesicles:</emphasis> Store the neurotransmitter until its release into the synaptic cleft.</item>
<item><emphasis>Neurotransmitter:</emphasis> After synthesis via enzyme catalyzed reactions in the cytosol of the axon terminal, the neurotransmitter molecules are housed in the synaptic vesicles of the presynaptic neuron.</item>
<item><emphasis>Reuptake channels:</emphasis> To be effective, the signal must be rapidly terminated. One mechanism is to remove the neurotransmitter, or some of the molecules from its degradation, from the synaptic cleft and return them to the presynaptic cytosol for recycling. Reuptake is an active transport process.</item></list><list id="eip-574"><title>Synaptic Cleft</title><item><emphasis>Neurotransmitter:</emphasis> when released into the cleft by the presynaptic neuron.</item>
<item><emphasis>Floating neurotransmitter degradation enzymes:</emphasis> A second way to terminate a signal is degradation of the neurotransmitter by an enzyme. In some cases these degradation enzymes are secreted into the synaptic cleft.</item>
</list><list id="eip-403"><title>Postsynaptic Neuron (Membrane)</title><item><emphasis>Ligand Receptors:</emphasis> Ligand receptors are located on the membrane of the cell bodies and dendrites of postsynaptic cells. You should recall that these receptors respond when a ligand, in this case the neurotransmitter, binds to the receptor. The receptors are either part of direct ligand-gated channel proteins or they activate G-proteins which then open or close channels that are part of a separate protein. Either way, the result generates or alters the membrane potential of the postsynaptic cell.</item>
<item><emphasis>Ion channels:</emphasis> are directly or indirectly altered by neurotransmitter/receptor binding, allowing or inhibiting the entry or exit of specific ions.</item>
<item><emphasis>Anchored neurotransmitter degradation enzymes:</emphasis> Perform the same functions as their floating counterparts but are attached to the postsynaptic membrane.</item>

</list><para id="eip-376"><link target-id="fig-ch12_05_03" document=""/> shows a synapse between a presynaptic and postsynaptic neuron.</para><para id="eip-142"><figure id="fig-ch12_05_03">   
<title>The Synapse</title>   
<media id="fs-id2211208" alt="This diagram shows a postsynaptic neuron. An axon from a presynaptic neuron is synapsing with the dendrites on the post synaptic neuron. The axon of the presynaptic neuron branches into several club shaped axon terminals. A magnified view of one of the synapses reveals that the axon terminal does not contact the dendrite of the postsynaptic neuron. Instead, there is a small space between the two structures, called the synaptic cleft. The axon terminal of the presynaptic neuron contains several synaptic vesicles, each holding about a dozen neurotransmitter particles. The synaptic vesicles travel to the edge of the axon terminal and release their neurotransmitters into the synaptic clefts The neurotransmitters travel through the synaptic cleft and bind to carrier proteins on the postsynaptic neuron that contain receptors for neurotransmitters.">
