</media>
<caption>The synapse is a connection between a neuron and its postsynaptic cell. Ca<sup>2+</sup> enters the presynaptic axon terminal to cause vesicle fusion and neurotransmitter release. The neurotransmitter diffuses across the synaptic cleft to bind to its receptor. The neurotransmitter is cleared from the synapse either by enzymatic degradation, neuronal reuptake, or diffusion away from the cleft.</caption> 
</figure>
</para></section><section id="fs-id1272286">
<title>Neurotransmitter Release</title>
<para id="fs-id2211233">Now that you have the anatomy of the synapse, let’s focus in on the events occurring at the synapse. When an action potential reaches the axon terminals, voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+</sup> channels in the membrane of the axon terminal open. Calcium influx occurs causing the concentration of calcium to increase inside the axon terminal, and the Ca<sup>2+</sup> ions associate with proteins in the outer surface of neurotransmitter vesicles. The Ca<sup>2+</sup> facilitates the fusion of the vesicle with the presynaptic membrane so that the neurotransmitter is released through exocytosis into the small gap between the cells, the <term>synaptic cleft</term>. The number of vesicles that fuse to the membrane and release neurotransmitter is related to the amount of intracellular Ca<sup>2+</sup>. </para><para id="fs-id1953662">Once in the synaptic cleft, the neurotransmitter rapidly diffuses the short distance to the postsynaptic membrane and binds to receptors on that membrane. The postsynaptic receptors may either be part of a channel protein where binding opens the channel, or they may activate a G-protein that ultimately opens or closes a channel that is part of a separate protein. All the receptors and channels at a specific synapse are the same type and the neurotransmitter released at a synapse have a high affinity for those receptors on the postsynaptic membrane.</para><para id="eip-485">Once the stimulus is removed from the presynaptic neuron, vesicle fusion and neurotransmitter release stop. The neurotransmitter already in the synaptic cleft must be removed. This process is dependent on the specific neurotransmitter but may include enzymatic degradation, reuptake, and/or diffusion away from the synaptic cleft (<link target-id="fig-ch12_05_03" document=""/>). Receptor-ligand binding is a reversible process, so removal of the neurotransmitter from the cleft results in ligand disengagement from the receptor and return of the channels to their resting state.</para></section>
<note id="eip-664"><label/>
<media id="fs-id1739411" alt="QR Code representing a URL">
<image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/neurotrans.png" width="120"/>
</media>
<para id="fs-id1739421">Watch this <link url="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/neurotrans">video</link> to learn about the release of a neurotransmitter. The action potential reaches the end of the axon, called the axon terminal, and a chemical signal is released to tell the target cell to do something—either to initiate a new action potential, or to suppress that activity. In a very short space, the electrical signal of the action potential is changed into the chemical signal of a neurotransmitter and then back to electrical changes in the target cell membrane. What is the importance of voltage-gated calcium channels in the release of neurotransmitters?</para>
</note><section id="fs-id1859928"><title>Neurotransmitters</title><para id="eip-676">Before beginning this section, you might want to review the <emphasis effect="italics">Types of Signal Molecules</emphasis> section in the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Communication</emphasis> chapter as neurotransmitters fall into the classes of signal molecules discussed there. This and future sections will expand on the applications of these classes of molecules.</para><para id="eip-463">Like other ligand signalling systems, the effect of the neurotransmitter is entirely dependent on the receptor. If there is no receptor protein in the membrane of the postsynaptic element, then the neurotransmitter has no effect. If there is a receptor, the effect, depolarizing or hyperpolarizing the membrane, is dependent on the receptor type and transduction pathway the receptor protein activates in that cell. Neurotransmitters bind to one of two classes of receptors at the cell surface, ionotropic or metabotropic (<link target-id="fig-ch12_05_04" document=""/>).  



</para><para id="eip-733"><figure id="fig-ch12_05_04"><title>Receptor Types</title><media id="fs-id2248857" alt="This diagram contains two images, labeled A and B. Both images show a cross section of a postsynaptic membrane. There are two proteins embedded in each of the two membrane cross sections. In diagram A, direct activation brings about an immediate response. Here, both of the membrane proteins are ion channels. Several hexagonal neurotransmitters bind to ionotropic receptors on the extracellular fluid side of the channels. The binding of neurotransmitters causes the channels to open, allowing ions to flow from the extracellular fluid into the cytosol. Image B shows indirect activation, which involves a prolonged response, amplified over time. Here, one of the cell membrane proteins is solid while the other is a channel. Neurotransmitters bind to metabotropic receptors on the extracellular side of the solid protein. This triggers the solid protein to activate a G protein in the cytoplasm. The G protein binds to an effector protein in the cytoplasm, which results in the production of several second messenger particles. The second messenger activates enzymes that open the channel protein, allowing ions to enter the cytoplasm.">
<image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/1226_Receptor_Types.jpg" width="400"/>
</media>
 
<caption>(a) An ionotropic receptor is a channel that opens when the neurotransmitter binds to it. (b) A metabotropic receptor is a complex that causes metabolic changes in the cell when the neurotransmitter binds to it (1). After binding, the G protein hydrolyzes GTP and moves to the effector protein (2). When the G protein contacts the effector protein, a second messenger is generated, such as cAMP (3). The second messenger can then go on to cause changes in the neuron, such as opening or closing ion channels, metabolic changes, and changes in gene transcription.</caption></figure></para><para id="eip-758"><emphasis>Ionotropic receptors</emphasis> are ligand-gated ion channels. You should recall from the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Communication</emphasis> chapter that this means the receptor is part of the channel protein. As a result, these channels are often referred to as <emphasis effect="italics">fast</emphasis> due to their quick opening when the ligand binds. The neurotransmitter opens the channel, which alters the electrical properties of the adjacent cell membrane. Examples of ionotropic receptors include the excitatory nicotinic receptors for acetylcholine and the inhibitory glycine receptors. </para><para id="eip-633"><emphasis>Metabotropic receptors</emphasis> on the other hand are G-protein-gated channels with the receptor and the ion channel on separate proteins. They are called metabotropic because metabolic action is required for the receptor to communicate with the ion channel. Recall that the G stands for guanosine and the G-protein is a complex of three subunits, alpha, beta, and gamma which are activated when the GDP is replaced by a GTP. When activated one of two things may happen depending on the transduction pathway in the cell, direct coupling of a G-protein subunit to the channel, or activation of a second messenger. Direct coupling will result in the opening or closing of ion channels which alters the electrical charge of the cell membrane; whereas, activation of a second messenger could entail opening or closing of ion channels along with other cell activities like activating transcription factors. </para><para id="eip-907">The communication between the two proteins results in a slower response time than an ionotropic receptor. Therefore, metabotropic receptors are often called <emphasis effect="italics">slow</emphasis> receptors. When the ligand binds to the receptor it activates a G-protein. Examples of metabotropic receptors include the muscarinic receptor for acetylcholine and the adrenergic receptors.</para><para id="fs-id2211430">The <term>cholinergic system</term> was not discussed specifically in the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Communication</emphasis> chapter. This system is based on acetylcholine (ACh); a hydrophilic signaling molecule not based on amino acids. Acetylcholine is an important neurotransmitter involved in both the central and peripheral nervous systems. Centrally it is involved in maintaining arousal, attention, and motivation. Peripherally it is an important neurotransmitter in both the voluntary and autonomic nervous systems.   </para><para id="eip-929">Acetylcholine is synthesized in the axon terminal of presynaptic neurons from two substrates, acetyl CoA and choline via choline acetyl transferase (CAT). Acetylcholine is broken down when it binds to the enzyme acetylcholinesterase (AChE) which is located on either the presynaptic or postsynaptic membranes. Recall from the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Respiration</emphasis> chapter that Acetyl CoA is a two-carbon molecule produced as a result of pyruvate oxidation during cellular respiration.  Choline however, cannot be synthesized and must be obtained from our diet. When acetylcholine is degraded the products are acetate and choline.  Choline is conserved using reuptake molecules on the presynaptic neuron to be used in the synthesis of more acetylcholine; acetate diffuses away from the synapse and enters the blood.</para><para id="eip-747">Acetylcholine binds to both ionotropic and metabotropic receptors. When acetylcholine binds to its ionotropic receptor, called a nicotinic receptor, the postsynaptic cell is depolarized. This is because the receptor is a cation channel so both sodium influx and potassium efflux occurs. Because more sodium enters the cell than K<sup>+</sup> leaving, the net effect is depolarization. However, when acetylcholine binds to its metabotropic receptor, called a muscarinic receptor (of which there are several variants) it might cause either depolarization or hyperpolarization of the target cell depending on the specific transduction pathway available in that target cell.</para><para id="fs-id1301668">The <term>nicotinic receptor</term>, a type of ionotropic receptor, is found at Neuro-Muscular Junctions (NJM), on the postganglionic neurons of the autonomic nervous system, and at other synapses in the body. The <term>muscarinic receptor</term>, a type of metabotropic (G-protein) receptor, is found at parasympathetic-effector junctions and other synapses. Both of these receptors are named for drugs that bind to their specific acetylcholine receptor type. Nicotine binds to the nicotinic receptor. Muscarine, a poisonous product of certain mushrooms, binds to the muscarinic receptor. Note that nicotine will not bind to a muscarinic receptor and muscarine will not bind to a nicotinic receptor.</para><para id="eip-31">To summarize what was stated above, the effect of acetylcholine on the postsynaptic element is entirely dependent on the receptor protein and the transduction pathway it activates in the postsynaptic cell. If there is no receptor protein in the membrane of the postsynaptic element, then the neurotransmitter has no effect. The effect, depolarizing or hyperpolarizing the membrane, also is dependent on the receptor type and the active pathways in the target cell. When acetylcholine binds to a nicotinic receptor, the postsynaptic cell is depolarized. However, when acetylcholine binds to a muscarinic receptor, it might cause depolarization or hyperpolarization of the target cell, as well as other cellular responses, depending on the specific transduction pathways available in the target cell.</para><para id="fs-id2073774"><emphasis>Amino acids</emphasis> are another class of neurotransmitters that were discussed in the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Communication</emphasis> chapter. These are important neurotransmitters in the central nervous system. The four amino acids that act as neurotransmitters are glutamate (Glu) and aspartate (Asp), which both activate excitatory receptors, and GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid, a derivative of glutamate) and glycine (Gly), which activate inhibitory receptors. These amino acids have an amino group and a carboxyl group in their chemical structures. Glutamate also is one of the 20 amino acids that are used to make proteins. Each amino acid neurotransmitter is part of its own system, namely the glutamatergic, aspartategic, GABAergic, and glycinergic systems. They each have their own receptors, although aspartate seems to target glutamatergic receptors generating a similar but less potent effect. Amino acid neurotransmitters are removed from the synapse by reuptake. A pump in the cell membrane of the presynaptic element, or sometimes a neighboring glial cell, will clear the amino acid from the synaptic cleft so that it can be recycled, repackaged in vesicles, and released again.</para><para id="eip-481">The amino acid neurotransmitters are almost exclusively associated with just one effect. Glutamate and aspartate are considered excitatory amino acids, because their receptors in the adult cause depolarization of the postsynaptic cell. Glycine and GABA are considered inhibitory amino acids, again because their receptors cause hyperpolarization. Glutamate is generally acknowledged as the most important neurotransmitter for normal brain function. Nearly all the excitatory neurons in the CNS are glutamatergic, and it is estimated that over half of all brain synapses release glutamate. The NMDA receptor that appears to be critical for the synaptic plasticity allowing memory and learning is a glutamate receptor. These NMDA receptors also are affected by many psychoactive drugs and appear to be responsible for their psychogenic effects. Aspartate appears to act on the same receptors as glutamate, but with less potency. </para><para id="fs-id1987875"><term>Biogenic amines</term>, another class of neurotransmitter discussed in the <emphasis effect="italics">Cellular Communication</emphasis> chapter, are made enzymatically from amino acids. They have amino groups in them, but no longer have carboxyl groups and are therefore no longer classified as amino acids. Biogenic amines play an important role in behavior and mental illness (i.e., bipolar disorder Schizophrenia, and depression.) </para><para id="eip-927">The biogenic amines have mixed effects. For example, the dopamine receptors that are classified as D1 receptors are excitatory whereas D2-type receptors are inhibitory. Biogenic amine receptors and neuropeptide receptors can have even more complex effects because some may not directly affect the membrane potential, but through their second messenger activation have an effect on gene transcription or other metabolic processes in the neuron. </para><para id="eip-515"><emphasis effect="italics">Serotonin</emphasis> is a biogenic amine made from tryptophan. It is the basis of the serotonergic system in the central nervous system, which has its own specific receptors. Serotonin is important in regulating sleep and our emotions. Serotonin is removed from the synapse by reuptake back into the presynaptic cell for repackaging. Antidepressants known as SSRIs (Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors), like the drug Prozac, block these reuptake channels prolonging the effect of serotonin in the synapse.</para><para id="fs-id1987885"><emphasis effect="italics">Catecholamines</emphasis>: <emphasis effect="italics">dopamine</emphasis>, <emphasis effect="italics">norepinephrine</emphasis>, and <emphasis effect="italics">epinephrine</emphasis> are biogenic amines made from tyrosine. Dopamine is part of its own system, the dopaminergic system, which has dopamine receptors. Dopamine is removed from the synapse by transport proteins in the presynaptic cell membrane. Norepinephrine and epinephrine belong to the <emphasis effect="italics">adrenergic</emphasis> neurotransmitter system. The two molecules are very similar and bind to the same receptors, which are referred to as alpha and beta adrenergic receptors. Norepinephrine and epinephrine are also actively transported back into the presynaptic cell. The chemical epinephrine (epi- = “on”; “-nephrine” = kidney) is also known as adrenaline (renal = “kidney”), and norepinephrine is sometimes referred to as noradrenaline. Recall that the adrenal gland produces epinephrine and norepinephrine to be released into the blood stream as hormones.</para><para id="eip-141">There are five different adrenergic receptors.  Both epinephrine and norepinephrine bind to these receptors; however, their affinities may vary as well as the location of these receptors and the second messenger system activated as a result of the neurotransmitter binding (<link target-id="eip-217" document=""/>).</para><table id="eip-217" summary="Lists the five adernergic receptor, their affinities to bind epinephrine and norepinephrine, their functions, and tissues the receptors can be find in."><title>The Adernergic Receptors</title>
