</table><para id="eip-429">Note that the effect of cAMP varies with the tissue type and anatomical location. Generally, an increase in cAMP will result in relaxation of smooth muscle (although there are exceptions) while it will increase contractility and heart rate in cardiac muscle. Additionally, increasing cAMP stimulates lypolysis in adipose cells and activates platelets in the blood.</para><para id="eip-668"><emphasis effect="italics">Histamine</emphasis> is another biogenic-amine neurotransmitter.  Histamine is derived from the amino acid, histidine. As a neurotransmitter, histamine plays a role in the hypothalamus by increasing wakefulness and inhibiting sleep. While histamine is important in many different body systems, it probably is best known as a paracrine ligand that triggers allergy symptoms. Many antihistamines targeting allergy symptoms also affect the neurotransmitter functions, which is why a side effect is drowsiness.</para><para id="fs-id1258863"><term>Neuropeptides</term> are neurotransmitter molecules made up of chains of amino acids connected by peptide bonds. This is what a protein is, but the term protein implies a certain length to the molecule. Some neuropeptides are quite short, such as met-enkephalin, which is five amino acids long. Others are long, such as beta-endorphin, which is 31 amino acids long. Neuropeptides are often released at synapses in combination with another neurotransmitters, and they often act as hormones in other systems of the body, such as antidiuretic hormone, oxytocin, thyrotropin releasing hormone (TRH), and corticotropin releasing hormone (CRH).</para><para id="eip-826">The characteristics of the various neurotransmitter systems presented in this section are summarized in <link target-id="tbl-ch12_03" document=""/>.</para><table id="tbl-ch12_03" summary="Describes the characteristics of neurotransmitter systems.">
