<title>Disorders of the…</title>
<para id="fs-id1501156"><title>Nervous System</title>The underlying cause of some neurodegenerative diseases, such as Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s, appears to be related to proteins—specifically, to proteins behaving badly. One of the strongest theories of what causes Alzheimer’s disease is based on the accumulation of beta-amyloid plaques, dense conglomerations of a protein that is not functioning correctly. Parkinson’s disease is linked to an increase in a protein known as alpha-synuclein that is toxic to the cells of the substantia nigra nucleus in the midbrain.</para><para id="fs-id1493614">For proteins to function correctly, they are dependent on their three-dimensional shape. The linear sequence of amino acids folds into a three-dimensional shape that is based on the interactions between and among those amino acids. When the folding is disturbed, and proteins take on a different shape, they stop functioning correctly. But the disease is not necessarily the result of functional loss of these proteins; rather, these altered proteins start to accumulate and may become toxic. For example, in Alzheimer’s, the hallmark of the disease is the accumulation of these amyloid plaques in the cerebral cortex. The term coined to describe this sort of disease is “proteopathy” and it includes other diseases. Creutzfeld-Jacob disease, the human variant of the prion disease known as mad cow disease in the bovine, also involves the accumulation of amyloid plaques, similar to Alzheimer’s. Diseases of other organ systems can fall into this group as well, such as cystic fibrosis or type 2 diabetes. Recognizing the relationship between these diseases has suggested new therapeutic possibilities. Interfering with the accumulation of the proteins, and possibly as early as their original production within the cell, may unlock new ways to alleviate these devastating diseases.</para>
</note>
</section></section>
<section id="eip-922"><title>Combining Neurons Into Networks</title><para id="eip-332">In the section on Action Potentials we discussed how an individual neuron integrates the input from other neurons and sensory cells and responds either by generating an action potential or remaining quiet. The basis of higher level sensory integration and response is the ability to combine neuron outputs and inputs into logical patterns or networks. This allows better discrimination of changes in the environment and more nuanced responses. These neuronal networks also form the physical basis of higher level functions like memory and learning.
</para><para id="eip-69">Multiple terminals from a single axon can form synapses with the same postsynaptic neuron. The number of synapses determines the strength of the connection between two neurons. The strength of the connection increases because an action potential is propagated to all of the axon's terminals. If there are enough synapses from a single axon the spacial summation can insure that the postsynaptic membrane will reach threshold. Postsynaptic neurons with enough connections from a single neuron to reach threshold are said to be in the <emphasis>discharge zone</emphasis> of that presynaptic neuron. Those with weaker connections (fewer single-axon synapses) are referred to as being in the <emphasis>facilitated zone</emphasis> because while one presynaptic neuron can facilitate moving the postsynaptic membrane potential toward threshold, it requires synapses from other neurons for the membrane to actually reach threshold. The more connections a single neuron has with a postsynaptic neuron, the more likely its signal will be propagated to the next level in the network when that neuron fires <link target-id="fig-Disharge_Zone" document=""/>. </para><para id="eip-484"><figure id="fig-Disharge_Zone"><media id="mid-Disharge_Zone" alt="This image shows a single presynaptic neuron with multiple axon terminals making synapses with several postsynaptic neurons. There are more individual synapses with some post synaptic neurons than with others. Those with the most synapses are in what is called the discharge zone. Those with fewer synapses are in what is called the facilitated zone.">
<image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Disharge_Zone.jpg" width="400"/>
</media>
 
<caption>The postsynaptic neurons with the most synapses are in the discharge zone, because a single presynaptic action potential will activate enough synapses to bring them to threshold. The postsynaptic neurons with fewer synapses are in the facilitated zone, because a single presynaptic action potential will not bring them to threshold. However, it will cause a graded potential that, with the assistance of synapses from other presynaptic neurons, will facilitate movement toward threshold.</caption></figure></para><para id="eip-347">The various combinations of neuronal connections are immense. Like the logic circuits of a computer, these neuronal circuits perform very specific processing activities. In turn, these simple modules can be combined in different combinations to perform specific higher-level processing modules. This hierarchy of modular processing ultimately reaches the levels of complexity that make up our higher level cognitive functioning. We will discuss only a few of the low level connection patterns below <link target-id="fig-Neuron_Networks" document=""/>.  </para><para id="eip-379"><figure id="fig-Neuron_Networks"><media id="mid-Neuron_Networks" alt="This image shows several basic patterns for linking neurons together. The first pattern shows a simple feed forward chain where each neuron influences the next neuron in the chain. The second pattern shows a basic feedback or reverberating loop where a neuron later in the chain influences a neuron earlier in the chain. The third pattern shows a convergent-divergent pattern. In convergence the output of several neurons converge on a single interneuron. In divergence a single interneuron provides output to multiple neurons. The fourth pattern shows a parallel after discharge chain where a neuron early in the chain diverges to stimulate more than one chain of neurons each running in parallel to the same target. Further down the chain these parallel chains converge back to influence the target neuron in the original chain. The final pattern shows lateral inhibition. Here the output of the originating neuron diverges with one path continuing to the target while others stimulate neurons that inhibit nearby neurons. These are primarily found in sensory processing to help discriminate edges and sharp contrasts in input.">
<image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Neuron_Networks.jpg" width="550"/>
</media>
 
<caption>This figure shows a few basic logic circuits that can be created by connecting neurons into different patterns. Note that the same basic pattern can be constructed with either excitatory or inhibitory interneurons at various locations. This increases the diversity of processing possibilities.</caption></figure></para><para id="eip-46">The general concepts of feed forward and feedback systems were discussed in the first chapter <emphasis effect="italics">Introduction to Human Physiology</emphasis>. We also have covered many of these general regulatory mechanisms in subsequent chapters. However, if you feel you have not mastered these concepts you might find a quick review of <emphasis effect="italics">Introduction to Human Physiology</emphasis> useful. The basic neural circuits are all variants of the cause and effect processes introduced earlier.</para><para id="eip-246">The concept of a <emphasis>Feed Forward</emphasis> system forms the basis of all processing. It is basically a processing chain where the neurons earlier in the chain influence those later in the chain. Because a single neuron generally has many axon terminals, neurons at each level of the chain can signal multiple neurons below it in the chain (see divergence below). In its pure form this would create a hierarchical network. It is feed forward because all the signals travel in the same direction without a feedback circuit.</para><para id="eip-72"><emphasis>Feedback</emphasis> happens when a neuron further down the chain synapses either directly, or through one or more interneurons, with a neuron earlier in the chain. If the feedback is excitatory the effect is a self-stimulating amplification in the circuit referred to as reverberation. <emphasis>Reverberating</emphasis> circuits help sustain a response and a similar concept in digital logic is used in solid-state memory devices. If the feedback is inhibitory, the effect is self damping and helps to reduce the response.</para><para id="eip-865"><emphasis>Convergence</emphasis> occurs when multiple presynaptic neurons synapse with (converge on) the same postsynaptic neuron. Functionally this is how input from multiple sources is integrated into a single response. <emphasis>Divergence</emphasis> occurs when a single presynaptic neuron synapses with (diverges to) multiple postsynaptic neurons. Functionally this is how widespread neural signalling occurs. A number of specific areas of the brain have been identified that have unusually high concentrations of both convergent and divergent inputs and outputs. Many are areas where multi-sensory integration and response take place, and they have been suggested as key brain areas involved in generating consciousness and self awareness.</para><para id="eip-741"><emphasis>Parallel After Discharge</emphasis> circuits are a feed forward mechanism for enhancing or amplifying an effect. Unlike a feedback system which affect neurons earlier in the chain, after discharge systems affect neurons further down the chain. In these circuits, the presynaptic neuron diverges to multiple postsynaptic neurons. These neurons, or their chains, ultimately converge back onto a neuron further down the original chain. The ultimate effect can be either stimulatory or inhibitory depending on the types of neurons in the parallel chains. </para><para id="eip-842"><emphasis>Lateral Inhibition</emphasis>, is common in some sensory circuits, particularly those involved in vision. The axons of the main presynaptic neurons in these circuits diverge to stimulate both an excitatory chain of neurons and a set of inhibitory neurons. The inhibitory neurons hyperpolarize the membranes of the presynaptic neurons immediately around the stimulated neuron. By inhibiting competing input from the surrounding neurons the brain is better able to accentuate the point of strongest stimulation making it easier to identify contrasting edges and boundaries. </para></section><section id="fs-id1862560" class="summary">
<title>Section Review</title><para id="fs-id2286155"><emphasis>Synapses</emphasis> are the contacts between neurons, which can either be chemical or electrical in nature. <emphasis>Chemical synapses</emphasis> are far more common than <emphasis>electrical junctions</emphasis>. At a chemical synapse, neurotransmitter is released from the presynaptic element and diffuses across the synaptic cleft. The neurotransmitter binds to a receptor protein and causes a change in the postsynaptic membrane (the PSP). The neurotransmitter must be inactivated or removed from the synaptic cleft so that the stimulus is limited in time.</para><para id="fs-id1639673">The particular characteristics of a synapse vary based on the neurotransmitter system produced by that neuron. The <emphasis>cholinergic system</emphasis> is found at the neuromuscular junction, in the autonomic nervous system, and in certain places within the body. Four <emphasis>amino acids</emphasis>: glutamate, aspartate, gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), and  glycine  are used as neurotransmitters. Other neurotransmitters are the result of amino acids being enzymatically changed, as in the <emphasis>biogenic amines</emphasis>, or being covalently bonded together, as in the <emphasis>neuropeptides</emphasis>.</para><para id="eip-278">Neuronal connections can be networked in patterns that allow for more sensitive discrimination of inputs about the environment, more nuanced responses, and higher level functions like memory and learning. Multiple axon terminals from a single axon can form synapses with a postsynaptic neuron. The number of synapses determines the strength of the connection between two neurons. Because an action potential is propagated to all of these terminals, if there are enough synapses from a single axon the spacial summation can insure that the postsynaptic membrane will reach threshold. Postsynaptic neurons with this type of connection are referred to as being in the <emphasis>discharge zone</emphasis> of the presynaptic neuron. Those with weaker connections are referred to as being in the <emphasis>facilitated zone</emphasis></para><para id="eip-1000">There are many different patterns of <emphasis>neuronal network connections</emphasis> that underlie the processing logic of all neural activity. Some common connection patterns are: <emphasis>feed forward</emphasis>, <emphasis>feedback/reverberating</emphasis>, <emphasis>parallel after discharge</emphasis>, <emphasis>convergent</emphasis>, <emphasis>divergent</emphasis>, and <emphasis>lateral inhibition</emphasis>.</para></section>
<section id="fs-id1639680" class="interactive-exercise">
<title>Interactive Link Questions</title>
<exercise id="fs-id1639687">
<problem id="fs-id1639689"><para id="fs-id1530911">Watch this <link url="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/summation">video</link> to learn about summation. The process of converting electrical signals to chemical signals and back requires subtle changes that can result in transient increases or decreases in membrane voltage. To cause a lasting change in the target cell, multiple signals are usually added together, or summated. Does spatial summation have to happen all at once, or can the separate signals arrive on the postsynaptic neuron at slightly different times? Explain your answer.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2543279">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id2543284">A second signal from a separate presynaptic neuron can arrive slightly later, as long as it arrives before the first one dies off, or dissipates.</para></solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2543289">
<problem id="fs-id2543291">
<para id="fs-id2543293">Watch this <link url="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/neurotrans">video</link> to learn about the release of a neurotransmitter. The action potential reaches the end of the axon, called the axon terminal, and a chemical signal is released to tell the target cell to do something, either initiate a new action potential, or to suppress that activity. In a very short space, the electrical signal of the action potential is changed into the chemical signal of a neurotransmitter, and then back to electrical changes in the target cell membrane. What is the importance of voltage-gated calcium channels in the release of neurotransmitters?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2317982">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id2317987">The action potential depolarizes the cell membrane of the axon terminal, which contains the voltage-gated Ca<sup>2+</sup> channel. That voltage change opens the channel so that Ca<sup>2+</sup> can enter the axon terminal. Calcium ions make it possible for synaptic vesicles to release their contents through exocytosis.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</section>
<section id="fs-id1230531" class="multiple-choice">
<title>Review Questions</title>
<exercise id="fs-id1859771">
<problem id="fs-id1099364"><para id="fs-id1015571">How much of a change in the membrane potential is necessary for the summation of postsynaptic potentials to result in an action potential being generated?</para>
<list id="fs-id1230543" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>+30 mV</item>
<item>+15 mV</item>
<item>+10 mV</item>
<item>-15 mV</item>
</list>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1497364">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id912818">B</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id890519">
<problem id="fs-id2167220"><para id="fs-id1494511">A channel opens on a postsynaptic membrane that causes a negative ion to enter the cell. What type of graded potential is this?</para>
<list id="fs-id1493303" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>depolarizing</item>
<item>repolarizing</item>
<item>hyperpolarizing</item>
<item>non-polarizing</item>
</list>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1164823">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id1404772">C</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1828568">
<problem id="fs-id2190800"><para id="fs-id1527310">What neurotransmitter is released at the neuromuscular junction?</para>
<list id="fs-id1104180" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>norepinephrine</item>
<item>serotonin</item>
<item>dopamine</item>
<item>acetylcholine</item>
</list>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1452835">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id963410">D</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1532169">
<problem id="fs-id1943845"><para id="fs-id1272928">What type of receptor requires an effector protein to initiate a signal?</para>
<list id="fs-id1113884" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>biogenic amine</item>
<item>ionotropic receptor</item>
<item>cholinergic system</item>
<item>metabotropic receptor</item></list>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1179935">
<label/><para id="fs-id1334770">D</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2317736">
<problem id="fs-id1144077"><para id="fs-id1944092">Which of the following neurotransmitters is associated with inhibition exclusively?</para>
<list id="fs-id1183736" list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha">
<item>GABA</item>
<item>acetylcholine</item>
<item>glutamate</item>
<item>norepinephrine</item></list>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1211547">
<label/>
<para id="fs-id1543381">A</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</section>
<section id="fs-id1716294" class="free-response">
<title>Critical Thinking Questions</title>
<exercise id="fs-id891267">
<problem id="fs-id1451945"><para id="fs-id1531347">If a postsynaptic cell has synapses from five different cells, and three cause EPSPs and two of them cause IPSPs, give an example of a series of depolarizations and hyperpolarizations that would result in the neuron reaching threshold.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1512606"><label/>
<para id="fs-id1143996">EPSP1 = +5 mV, EPSP2 = +7 mV, EPSP 3 = +10 mV, IPSP1 = -4 mV, IPSP2 = -3 mV. 5 + 7 + 10 – 4 – 3 = +15 mV.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1188256">
<problem id="fs-id1138838"><para id="fs-id1955545">Why is the receptor the important element determining the effect a neurotransmitter has on a target cell?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2168882"><label/>
<para id="fs-id1868224">Different neurotransmitters have different receptors. Thus, the type of receptor in the postsynaptic cell is what determines which ion channels open. Acetylcholine binding to the nicotinic receptor causes cations to cross the membrane. GABA binding to its receptor causes the anion chloride to cross the membrane.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</section>
